==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Housewife
<hw>House"wife`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>House</ets>
+ <ets>wife.</ets> Cf. <er>Hussy</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The wife
of a householder; the mistress of a family; the female head of a
household.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He a good husband, a good <qex>housewife</qex> she.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <pr>(Usually pronounced <?/.)</pr> <ety>[See
<er>Hussy</er>, in this sense.]</ety> <def>A little case or bag for
materials used in sewing, and for other articles of female work; --
called also <altname>hussy</altname>.</def> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>huswife</asp>.]</altsp> <rj><au>P. Skelton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A hussy.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> <altsp>[Usually
written <asp>huswife</asp>.]</altsp> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Sailor's housewife</b></col>, <cd>a
ditty-bag.</cd></cs></p>

<p><ent>Housewive</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Housewife</ent>⟦br⟧
